Google Trends analysis of teledermatology interest

Loading libraries

First, we will load the libraries used for the analysis and figures.

library(gtrendsR)
library(data.table)
library(dplyr)
library(ggplot2)

Figure 1

We will get monthly search volume from Google Trends for telehealth and dermatology in the United States from January 01, 2017 to December 31, 2022.

derm.keywords = "telehealth dermatologist + teledoc dermatologist + virtual dermatologist"
start.date = "2017-01-01"
end.date = "2022-12-31"
region = c("US")

derm.res = gtrendsR::gtrends(keyword = derm.keywords,
                             geo = region,
                             gprop = "web",
                             low_search_volume = TRUE,
                             hl = "en-US",
                             time = paste(start.date, end.date))

Next, we will smooth the interest over time data over a three month period.

derm.interest.over.time.dt = as.data.table(derm.res$interest_over_time)
derm.interest.over.time.dt[, year := gsub("^(20[0-9]{2})-.*", "\\1", date)]
derm.interest.over.time.dt[, month := as.numeric(gsub("20[0-9]{2}-([0-9]{2})-[0-9]{2}", "\\1", date))]
derm.interest.over.time.dt[, quarter := cut(month, breaks = c(0, 3, 6, 9, 12), labels = c("Jan - Mar", "Apr - Jun", "Jul - Sep", "Oct - Dec"))]
derm.interest.over.time.dt[, label := paste(year, quarter)]
derm.interest.over.time.dt[, month_label := paste(year, quarter)]

derm.interest.over.time.dt[, label_level := ordered(label, levels = pt.dt[order(quarter)][order(year)][, unique(label)])]
derm.interest.over.time.dt[, time_period := ordered(ifelse(year < "2020", "pre-pandemic", ifelse(year == "2020", ifelse(month < 3, "pre-pandemic", "pandemic"), "pandemic")), levels = c("pre-pandemic", "pandemic"))]

pt.dt = derm.interest.over.time.dt[, .(hits = mean(hits)), by = .(label_level, time_period)]

Next we make a plot of our results.

pt = ggplot(pt.dt, aes(x = label_level, y = hits)) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_line(aes(x = as.numeric(label_level), y = hits)) + 
  labs(x = "date range", y = "relative search volume") +
  theme_bw() +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 90))

Figure 1a. Teledermatology interest from 2017-2022

We will use a boxplot to compare interest in dermatology before and after March 2020.

pt = ggplot(pt.dt, aes(x = time_period, y = hits)) +
  geom_boxplot(outlier.shape = NA) +
  geom_jitter(width = 0.1, height = 0, size = 0.3) +
  theme_bw() +
  labs(x = "period",  y = "relative search volume")

Figure 1a. Teledermatology interest from 2017-2022

Figure 2

In this analysis, we compare the interest in teledermatology with the interest in COVID-19 from January 01, 2020 to December 31, 2022. As before, we will get monthly search interest in each topic, and compute three month averages.

start.date = "2020-01-01"
end.date = "2022-12-01"
covid.res = gtrendsR::gtrends(keyword = c("COVID-19"),
                              geo = c("US"),
                              gprop = "web",
                              low_search_volume = TRUE,
                              hl = "en-US",
                              time = paste(start.date, end.date))

tderm.res = gtrendsR::gtrends(keyword = c("dermatologist telehealth + dermatologist virtual + dermatologist telemedicine"),
                              geo = c("US"),
                              gprop = "web",
                              low_search_volume = TRUE,
                              hl = "en-US",
                              time = paste(start.date, end.date))

covid.dt = as.data.table(covid.res$interest_over_time)
tderm.dt = as.data.table(tderm.res$interest_over_time)

merged.dt = rbind(covid.dt[, query := "COVID-19"], tderm.dt[, query := "teledermatology"])

## smooth by month
merged.dt[, year := gsub("^(20[0-9]{2})-.*", "\\1", date)]
merged.dt[, month := gsub("20[0-9]{2}-([0-9]{2})-[0-9]{2}", "\\1", date) %>% as.numeric]
merged.dt[, quarter := cut(month, breaks = c(0, 3, 6, 9, 12), labels = c("Jan - Mar", "Apr - Jun", "Jul - Sep", "Oct - Dec"))]
merged.dt[, label := paste(year, quarter)]
merged.dt[, block := ifelse(year == 2020, "2020", "2021-2022")]
pt.dt = merged.dt[, .(hits = base::mean(as.numeric(hits), na.rm = TRUE), block = block[1], year = year[1], quarter = quarter[1]), by = .(query, label)]

pt.dt[, label_level := ordered(label, levels = pt.dt[order(quarter)][order(year)][, unique(label)])]

pt = ggplot(pt.dt, aes(x = label_level, y = hits, color = query)) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_line(aes(x = as.numeric(label_level), y = hits)) + 
  labs(x = "date range", y = "normalized search count") +
  theme_bw() +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 90))

Figure 1a. Teledermatology interest from 2017-2022

Figure 2

In this analysis, we compare the interest in teledermatology with the interest in COVID-19 from January 01, 2020 to December 31, 2022. As before, we will get monthly search interest in each topic, and compute three month averages.

start.date = "2020-01-01"
end.date = "2022-12-01"
covid.res = gtrendsR::gtrends(keyword = c("COVID-19"),
                              geo = c("US"),
                              gprop = "web",
                              low_search_volume = TRUE,
                              hl = "en-US",
                              time = paste(start.date, end.date))

tderm.res = gtrendsR::gtrends(keyword = c("dermatologist telehealth + dermatologist virtual + dermatologist telemedicine"),
                              geo = c("US"),
                              gprop = "web",
                              low_search_volume = TRUE,
                              hl = "en-US",
                              time = paste(start.date, end.date))

covid.dt = as.data.table(covid.res$interest_over_time)
tderm.dt = as.data.table(tderm.res$interest_over_time)

## smooth by month
merged.dt[, year := gsub("^(20[0-9]{2})-.*", "\\1", date)]
merged.dt[, month := gsub("20[0-9]{2}-([0-9]{2})-[0-9]{2}", "\\1", date) %>% as.numeric]

Figure 2a. Teledermatology and COVID-19 relative search volumes during the COVID-19 pandemic

In addition, we will compute the cross-correlation between COVID-19 and teledermatology interest in the pre- and post-vaccine period.

merged.dt = merge.data.table(covid.dt[, .(date, covid = as.numeric(hits))], tderm.dt[, .(date, derm = as.numeric(hits))])
merged.dt[is.na(merged.dt)] = 0
merged.dt[, month := gsub("20[0-9]{2}-([0-9]{2})-[0-9]{2}", "\\1", date) %>% as.numeric]
merged.dt[, year := gsub("^(20[0-9]{2})-.*", "\\1", date)]
## merged.dt = merged.dt[, .(covid = mean(covid), derm = mean(derm)), by = .(year, month)]

pre.vaccine.correlation = merged.dt[year == "2020", stats::ccf(covid, derm)]
post.vaccine.correlation = merged.dt[year == "2021" | year == "2022", stats::ccf(covid, derm)]
## plot cross correlation
pt.dt = rbind(data.table(acf = pre.vaccine.correlation$acf,
                          lag = pre.vaccine.correlation$lag,
                          year = "pre-vaccine"),
               data.table(acf = post.vaccine.correlation$acf,
                          lag = post.vaccine.correlation$lag,
                          year = "post-vaccine"))

pt.dt[, year_level := ordered(year, levels = c("pre-vaccine", "post-vaccine"))]

pt = ggplot(pt.dt, aes(x = lag, y = acf)) +
  geom_bar(width = 0.3, stat = "identity") +
  facet_grid(rows = vars(year_level)) +
  theme_bw() +
  xlim(-8, 8) +
  ylim(-0.5, 0.5) +
  labs(x = "lag (weeks)", y = "cross-correlation")

Figure 2b. cross-correlation between COVID-19 and teledermatology interest in the pre- and post-vaccine periods

Figure 3

We will compare interest in the following specialties overall and in relation to telehealth: surgery, family medicine, dermatology, psychiatry.

specialty.kw = c("telehealth dermatologist + teledoc dermatologist + virtual dermatologist",
                 "telehealth family + teledoc family + virtual family doctor",
                 "teledoc psychiatrist + virtual psychiatrist + telehealth psychiatrist",
                 "virtual surgeon + telehealth surgery + teledoc surgery")

## divide into two queries
start.date = "2017-01-01"
end.date = "2020-05-01"
spec.res.1 = gtrendsR::gtrends(keyword = specialty.kw,
                             geo = c("US"),
                             low_search_volume = TRUE,
                             hl = "en-US",
                             time = paste(start.date, end.date))

start.date = "2020-05-02"
end.date = "2022-12-01"
spec.res.2 = gtrendsR::gtrends(keyword = specialty.kw,
                               geo = c("US"),
                               low_search_volume = TRUE,
                               hl = "en-US",
                               time = paste(start.date, end.date))

## comparison to other specialties (not virtual)
## comparison to other specialties
regular.kw = c("dermatologist + dermatology", "family doctor + family medicine + primary care + internal medicine", "psychiatry + psychiatrist", "surgeon + surgery")

## divide into two queries
start.date = "2017-01-10"
end.date = "2020-05-01"
reg.res.1 = gtrendsR::gtrends(keyword = regular.kw,
                             geo = c("US"),
                             gprop = "web",
                             low_search_volume = TRUE,
                             hl = "en-US",
                             time = paste(start.date, end.date))

start.date = "2020-05-02"
end.date = "2022-12-01"
reg.res.2 = gtrendsR::gtrends(keyword = regular.kw,
                               geo = c("US"),
                               gprop = "web",
                               low_search_volume = TRUE,
                               hl = "en-US",
                               time = paste(start.date, end.date))

spec.res.dt = rbind(
  as.data.table(spec.res.1$interest_over_time)[, type := "telehealth"],
  as.data.table(spec.res.2$interest_over_time)[, type := "telehealth"],
  as.data.table(reg.res.1$interest_over_time)[, type := "all"],
  as.data.table(reg.res.2$interest_over_time)[, type := "all"])

## simplify the keywords
spec.res.dt[grepl("derm", keyword), simplified.keyword := "dermatology"]
spec.res.dt[grepl("pedia", keyword), simplified.keyword := "pediatrics"]
spec.res.dt[grepl("family", keyword), simplified.keyword := "family medicine"]
spec.res.dt[grepl("psych", keyword), simplified.keyword := "psychiatry"]
spec.res.dt[grepl("dent", keyword), simplified.keyword := "dentistry"]
spec.res.dt[grepl("surg", keyword), simplified.keyword := "surgery"]

spec.res.dt[, year := gsub("^(20[0-9]{2})-.*", "\\1", date)]
spec.res.dt[, month := gsub("20[0-9]{2}-([0-9]{2})-[0-9]{2}", "\\1", date) %>% as.numeric]
spec.res.dt[, quarter := cut(month, breaks = c(0, 3, 6, 9, 12), labels = c("Jan - Mar", "Apr - Jun", "Jul - Sep", "Oct - Dec"))]
spec.res.dt[, label := paste(year, quarter)]
## order labels
spec.res.dt[, label_level := ordered(label, levels = pt.dt[order(quarter)][order(year)][, unique(label)])]

spec.res.dt[, time_period := ordered(ifelse(year < "2020", "pre-pandemic", ifelse(year == "2020", ifelse(month < 3, "pre-pandemic", "pandemic"), "pandemic")), levels = c("pre-pandemic", "pandemic"))]

pt.dt = spec.res.dt[, .(hits = median(hits),
                        max.hits = max(hits),
                        min.hits = min(hits),
                        time_period = time_period[1],
                        year = year[1]),
                    by = .(label_level, type, simplified.keyword)]

## make a plot of this...
pt = ggplot(pt.dt, aes(x = label_level, y = hits, color = simplified.keyword)) +
  geom_point(size = 1) +
  geom_line(aes(x = as.numeric(label_level), y = hits)) +
  facet_grid(rows = vars(type)) +
  labs(x = "date range", y = "relative search volume") +
  theme_bw() +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 90)) +
  theme(legend.position = "right")
print(pt)

Figure 3a specialty specific interest and telehealth interest 

## order hits
pt.dt[, kw.level := ordered(simplified.keyword, c("dermatology", "surgery", "family medicine", "psychiatry"))]
pt.dt[, procedural := ifelse(simplified.keyword == "surgery" | simplified.keyword == "dermatology", "procedural", "non-procedural")]

## boxplot of normalized counts by category
pt = ggplot(pt.dt, aes(x = kw.level, y = hits, color = procedural)) +
  geom_boxplot(outlier.shape = NA) +
  geom_jitter(size = 0.3, width = 0.1, alpha = 1) +
  facet_grid(cols = vars(type)) +
  labs(x = "specialty", y = "relative search volume") +
  theme_bw() +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 90)) +
  theme(legend.position = "bottom")
print(pt)

Figure 3b comparison of normalized search volume between specialties in the pre-pandemic and pandemic periods

Figure 4.

## seasonality
start.date = "2017-01-01"
end.date = "2022-12-01"
tderm.res = gtrendsR::gtrends(keyword = c("dermatologist telehealth + dermatologist virtual + dermatologist telemedicine"),
                              geo = c("US"),
                              gprop = "web",
                              low_search_volume = TRUE,
                              hl = "en-US",
                              time = paste(start.date, end.date))

nderm.res = gtrendsR::gtrends(keyword = "dermatologist",
                              geo = c("US"),
                              gprop = "web",
                              low_search_volume = TRUE,
                              hl = "en-US",
                              time = paste(start.date, end.date))


seasonal.dt = rbind(as.data.table(tderm.res$interest_over_time)[, type := "telehealth"],
                    as.data.table(nderm.res$interest_over_time)[, type := "normal"])

seasonal.dt[, year := gsub("^(20[0-9]{2})-.*", "\\1", date)]
seasonal.dt[, month := gsub("20[0-9]{2}-([0-9]{2})-[0-9]{2}", "\\1", date) %>% as.numeric]
seasonal.dt[, season := ifelse(month %in% c(4,5,6,7,8,9), "spring/summer", "fall/winter")]
seasonal.dt[, block := ifelse(year < 2020, "pre-pandemic", ifelse(year > 20202, "post-pandemic", "other"))]

pt = ggplot(seasonal.dt[block != "other"], aes(x = season, y = hits)) +
  geom_boxplot(outlier.shape = NA) +
  geom_jitter(width = 0.1, height = 0, size = 0.3) +
  facet_grid(cols = vars(type), rows = vars(block)) +
  theme_bw() +
  labs(x = "pre- versus post-pandemic",  y = "normalized search count")
print(pt)

Figure 4. Seasonality of dermatology and teledermatology interest
